    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-01-03T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-01-03T08:00:00-05:00" n="239"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d239">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 657.119/221</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Norway</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Schmedeman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Christiania</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-01-03T14:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 3, 1918—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 11.20 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>445. Irresponsible rumors are widely current here to the effect that the United
                    States Government is making a deliberate effort to force Norway into the war.
                    The Norwegian Government is apparently <pb facs="0274" n="1108" xml:id="pg_1108"
                    /> taking no steps to counteract the effect of these rumors, which are largely
                    due to secrecy and obscurity with which Norwegian Government surrounds the
                    present negotiations with the United States concerning imports. No information
                    whatsoever has been vouchsafed the public as to the real nature of American
                    demands, with the result that damaging speculation is rife as to their
                    character. Part of the press is attempting to allay excitement by general
                    statements that our demands involve no danger to Norway, but the creation of
                    sound opinion is handicapped by lack of accurate information.</p>
                <p>Under the circumstances, I submit for the Department’s consideration whether it
                    would not be desirable to publish a <hi rend="italic">communiqué</hi> at
                    Washington or elsewhere explaining in some detail the nature of our demands,
                    with particular emphasis on the fact that they are based on the principle of
                    compensation. London informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_SAG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Schmedeman</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
